{"title_page": "Collits' Inn (musical)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical\n| name = Collits' Inn\n| image = \n| caption = \n| music = [[Varney Monk]]\n| lyrics = [[Varney Monk]]\n| book = T. Stuart Gurr\n| basis = \n| productions = 1932 Savoy Theatre Sydney<ref>[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/indexdrilldown.jsp?xcid=59&f_event_id=25526 1932 Savoy Theatre Sydney production] at AusStage</ref><br>1933 Princess Theatre Melbourne<ref>[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/indexdrilldown.jsp?xcid=59&f_event_id=16548 1933 Melbourne production] at AusStage</ref><br>1934 New Tivoli Sydney<ref>[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/indexdrilldown.jsp?xcid=59&f_event_id=23127 1934 New Tivoli Sydney production] at AusStage</ref>\n| awards =\n}}\n'''''Collits' Inn''''' is an Australian musical play. The 1933 Melbourne production at the [[Princess Theatre, Melbourne|Princess Theatre]] was presented by [[F. W. Thring]] and starred [[Gladys Moncrieff]], [[George Wallace (Australian comedian)|George Wallace]], [[Claude Flemming]] and [[Campbell Copelin]]. Wallace's role was created especially for him.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article73270706 |title=EFFTEE FILM PRODUCTIONS. |newspaper=[[Frankston & Somerville Standard]] |location=Vic. |date=17 February 1934 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> It is generally considered the first commercially successful Australian musical.\n\n==Plot==\nLove and drama at a roadside tavern in the [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]] owned by former convict Pierce Collits, who built the [[Collits' Inn|eponymous inn]] on [[land grant]]ed to him at {{NSWcity|Hartley Vale}} in exchange for helping supervise construction of a road from {{NSWcity|Penrith}} to the western plans. Pierce's daughter Mary is in love with a young officer John Lake. However her father hates officers and refuses to give his blessing.\n\nBushranger Robert Keane is in love with Mary. He hits her and Lake kills him. Lake is ordered home and becomes a baron. When he returns he discovers Mary has lost her memory. However she regains it and all ends happily.\n\nComic relief is provided by the inn roustabout, Dandy Dick, who is in love with Sally the barmaid but faces competition from barman Toby.\n\n==Songs==\n*\"A Laugh and a Kiss\" by John Lake\n*\"Stay While the Stars Are Shining\" by John Lake and Mary Collits\n*\"Outlaws Song\" by Robert Keane\n*\"Sweet William\"\n*Aboriginal chant\n*\"Australia\" \u2013 the finale with John Lake and Mary Collits\n*\"Blue Mountains\"\n*\"The chaperone\"\n*Corroboree ballet\n*\"Dangerous Dandy Dick\"\n*\"Drinking song\"\n*\"Duddawarra River\"\n*\"Happy with you\"\n*\"How I love you\"\n*\"I'll wait for my true love\"\n*\"Last year\"\n*\"Making memories\"\n*\"The man in the cabbage tree hat\"\n*\"Melos\"\n*\"My desire\"\n*\"My valentine\"\n*\"Next year\"\n*\"Only you\"\n*\"The Redcoats\"\n*\"The road song\"\n*\"The rouseabout\"\n*\"Sally at the sliprail\"\n*\"See what loves done to me\"\n*\"Some distant day\"\n*\"Square dance\"\n*\"That's what love does to me\"\n*\"They're in love\"\n*\"This year\"\n*\"Waltz ballet\"\n*\"We're singing of Australia\"\n\n==Production history==\n===Development===\nIn 1932 Mosman neighbours Varney Monk and Stuart Gurr collaborated on a musical together in order to submit it to a competition for an original operetta or musical play. The competition was held by [[Nathalie Rosenwax]], a prominent Sydney singing teacher.<ref>{{Citation\n  | author1=Australasian Radio Relay League.\n  | title=The wireless weekly : the hundred per cent Australian radio journal,\n  | publication-date=\n  | publisher=Wireless Press\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-681474952\n  | accessdate=11 April 2019\n}}</ref>\n\nThe musical was based on Collits Inn, a real life inn established near Lithgow on the road from Sydney to Bathurst built by Irish convict Pierce Collits.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16897864 |title=THE COLLITS FAMILY. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=6 August 1932 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Monk and her husband Cyril, a violinist, had spent several holidays there and heard the story about how Pierce Collits daughter Amelia had been in love with a soldier. It is doubtful this story was actually true but it inspired Monk to write a musical around it.<ref name=\"john\"/>\n\nThe musical won second prize in the competition, losing to ''The Island of Pines'', but it was ''Collits Inn'' which Nathalie Ronenwax decided to produce with her students in lead roles. They did five performances at the Savoy Theatre from 5 December 1932, starring professional soprano [[Rene Maxwell]] as Mary Collit and radio personality Jack Winn in support.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16932126 |title=SAVOY THEATRE\u2014\"COLLITT'S INN.\". |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=19 November 1932 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16935627 |title=AN AUSTRALIAN OPERA. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=6 December 1932 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=15 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The musical was revised and performed again in March 1933 at the Mosman Town Hall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16955408 |title=\"COLLITS' INN\". AT MOSMAN. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=25 February 1933 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n</ref> It was also broadcast on ABC radio in June of that year. However it was turned down for professional production by J.C. Williamsons Ltd.\n\n===F. W. Thring===\nVarney Monk sent the script to Frank Thring and went down to Melbourne to play him the score.  Thring was enthusiastic about the show and decided to produce it professionally. He hired an all star cast, putting Gladys Moncrieff, Australia's most popular star of light opera under a 12-month contract to play the lead. He also brought back two Australians from overseas to appear opposite her, Robert Chisholm and Claude Fleming, and hired the most popular comic of the day, George Wallace, to play the comic support role of Dandy Dan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17033105 |title=MUSIC AND DRAMA. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=16 December 1933 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nWallace's presence in the cast meant his part was expanded and he was given as many songs as Glady Moncrieff; in addition, parts were found for his regular collaborators, Marshall Crosby and [[John Dobbie]]. Extra lures to the theatre-going audience was a revolving stage, the first of its kind used in Australia, and the performance of an aboriginal corroboree at the beginning of Act Two.\n\nThe resulting production debuted in December 1933. It was a widely publicised occasion, attended by the state premier and lord mayor and the first act was broadcast live on Radio 3KZ. \"All this excitement over an Australian show with an all-Australian cast\", wrote Thring's biographer, Peter Fitzpatrick. \"Nothing like it had happened before. Frank [Thring]... must have felt like a king... It was certainly the most triumphant night of his life.\"<ref>Fitzpatrick p 199</ref>\n\nThe show was a big success, receiving excellent reviews and playing for sixteen weeks and over a hundred performances at the Princess.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11724052 |title=MUSIC, DRAMA & FILMS \"COLLITS' INN\". |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=26 December 1933 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n</ref> It went to Sydney for eight weeks, then had a three-week return season in Melbourne in October 1934.\n\nThe success of the musical encouraged Thring to expand his theatrical productions. Thring commissioned Monk to write a sequel, ''[[The Cedar Tree (musical)|The Cedar Tree]]'' and also revived ''[[The Beloved Vagabond (play)|The Beloved Vagabond]]''.<ref>Fitzpatrick p 203</ref>\n\n===Cast of 1933 Princess Theatre production===\n*Gladys Moncrieff as Mary Collits\n*Marshall Crosby as Pierce Collits\n*Robert Chisholm as John Lake\n*Claude Flemming as Robert Keane\n*George Wallace as Dandy Dick\n*Phyllis Baker as Sandy\n*John Dobbie as Toby\n\n==Proposed film version==\nThring intended to make a movie out of the play but died in 1936 before he had the chance to shoot little more than sound tests.<ref>Graham Shirley and Brian Adams, ''Australian Cinema: The First Eighty Years'', Currency, 1989 p122</ref><ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17039526?searchTerm=%22streets%20of%20london%22%20thring&searchLimits=sortby=dateAsc|||l-category=Article%7Ccategory%3AArticle 'ENGLISH PLAYS To be Filmed in Melbourne', ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', Friday 12 January 1934 p 6]</ref> A six-minute sound test of [[Gladys Moncrieff]] and Robert Chisolm singing 'While the Stars Are Shining', with a spoken introduction by [[Frank Harvey (Australian screenwriter)|Frank Harvey]] survives.<ref>[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=collit's%20inn;querytype=;rec=8;resCount=10 Clip at National Film and Sound Archive]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Harvey had reportedly written a screenplay.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61874368 |title=STACK ASIDES. |newspaper=[[Townsville Daily Bulletin]] |location=Qld. |date=29 October 1934 |accessdate=7 December 2012 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the words of theatre historian John Thompson:\n<blockquote>Collits\u2019 Inn was hailed as a unique Australian musical. It was not the first theatrical production to use Australian settings, nor was it, as is commonly claimed, the first Australian musical... [It] was not The Great Australian Musical many hoped it would be. But it proved that Australian creativity and talent could produce an original work that Australian audiences wanted to see and was judged worthy of a place on the world stage.<ref name=\"john\">[http://www.australianmusicals.com/article_itsaustralian.htm John Thompson, \"It's Australian and It's Good\", National Library of Australia News, Dec 2003, reproduced in ''Australian Musicals''] accessed 4 October 2013</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*Fitzpatrick, Peter, ''The Two Frank Thrings'', Monash University Press 2012\n\n==External links==\n* [http://muchamore.id.au/The_Play.html Article on ''Collits' Inn'', the play]\n* [http://www.australianmusicals.com/article_itsaustralian.htm ''It's Australian and It's Good''] article on history of the show by John Thompson at [[National Library of Australia]] News\n*[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/work/1889 Collits Inn] at [[AusStage]]\n\n[[Category:Australian musicals]]\n[[Category:1932 musicals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical\n| name = Collits' Inn\n| image = \n| caption = \n| music = [[Varney Monk]]\n| lyrics = [[Varney Monk]]\n| book = T. Stuart Gurr\n| basis = \n| productions = 1932 Savoy Theatre Sydney<ref>[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/indexdrilldown.jsp?xcid=59&f_event_id=25526 1932 Savoy Theatre Sydney production] at AusStage</ref><br>1933 Princess Theatre Melbourne<ref>[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/indexdrilldown.jsp?xcid=59&f_event_id=16548 1933 Melbourne production] at AusStage</ref><br>1934 New Tivoli Sydney<ref>[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/indexdrilldown.jsp?xcid=59&f_event_id=23127 1934 New Tivoli Sydney production] at AusStage</ref>\n| awards =\n}}\n'''''Collits' Inn''''' is an Australian musical play. The 1933 Melbourne production at the [[Princess Theatre, Melbourne|Princess Theatre]] was presented by [[F. W. Thring]] and starred [[Gladys Moncrieff]], [[George Wallace (Australian comedian)|George Wallace]], [[Claude Flemming]] and [[Campbell Copelin]]. Wallace's role was created especially for him.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article73270706 |title=EFFTEE FILM PRODUCTIONS. |newspaper=[[Frankston & Somerville Standard]] |location=Vic. |date=17 February 1934 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> It is generally considered the first commercially successful Australian musical.\n\n==Plot==\nLove and drama at a roadside tavern in the [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]] owned by former convict Pierce Collits, who built the [[Collits' Inn|eponymous inn]] on [[land grant|land granted]] to him at {{NSWcity|Hartley Vale}} in exchange for helping supervise construction of a road from {{NSWcity|Penrith}} to the western plans. Pierce's daughter Mary is in love with a young officer John Lake. However her father hates officers and refuses to give his blessing.\n\nBushranger Robert Keane is in love with Mary. He hits her and Lake kills him. Lake is ordered home and becomes a baron. When he returns he discovers Mary has lost her memory. However she regains it and all ends happily.\n\nComic relief is provided by the inn roustabout, Dandy Dick, who is in love with Sally the barmaid but faces competition from barman Toby.\n\n==Songs==\n*\"A Laugh and a Kiss\" by John Lake\n*\"Stay While the Stars Are Shining\" by John Lake and Mary Collits\n*\"Outlaws Song\" by Robert Keane\n*\"Sweet William\"\n*Aboriginal chant\n*\"Australia\" \u2013 the finale with John Lake and Mary Collits\n*\"Blue Mountains\"\n*\"The chaperone\"\n*Corroboree ballet\n*\"Dangerous Dandy Dick\"\n*\"Drinking song\"\n*\"Duddawarra River\"\n*\"Happy with you\"\n*\"How I love you\"\n*\"I'll wait for my true love\"\n*\"Last year\"\n*\"Making memories\"\n*\"The man in the cabbage tree hat\"\n*\"Melos\"\n*\"My desire\"\n*\"My valentine\"\n*\"Next year\"\n*\"Only you\"\n*\"The Redcoats\"\n*\"The road song\"\n*\"The rouseabout\"\n*\"Sally at the sliprail\"\n*\"See what loves done to me\"\n*\"Some distant day\"\n*\"Square dance\"\n*\"That's what love does to me\"\n*\"They're in love\"\n*\"This year\"\n*\"Waltz ballet\"\n*\"We're singing of Australia\"\n\n==Production history==\n===Development===\nIn 1932 Mosman neighbours Varney Monk and Stuart Gurr collaborated on a musical together in order to submit it to a competition for an original operetta or musical play. The competition was held by [[Nathalie Rosenwax]], a prominent Sydney singing teacher.<ref>{{Citation\n  | author1=Australasian Radio Relay League.\n  | title=The wireless weekly : the hundred per cent Australian radio journal,\n  | publication-date=\n  | publisher=Wireless Press\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-681474952\n  | accessdate=11 April 2019\n}} </ref>\n\nThe musical was based on Collits Inn, a real life inn established near Lithgow on the road from Sydney to Bathurst built by Irish convict Pierce Collits.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16897864 |title=THE COLLITS FAMILY. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=6 August 1932 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Monk and her husband Cyril, a violinist, had spent several holidays there and heard the story about how Pierce Collits daughter Amelia had been in love with a soldier. It is doubtful this story was actually true but it inspired Monk to write a musical around it.<ref name=\"john\"/>\n\nThe musical won second prize in the competition, losing to ''The Island of Pines'', but it was ''Collits Inn'' which Nathalie Ronenwax decided to produce with her students in lead roles. They did five performances at the Savoy Theatre from 5 December 1932, starring professional soprano [[Rene Maxwell]] as Mary Collit and radio personality Jack Winn in support.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16932126 |title=SAVOY THEATRE\u2014\"COLLITT'S INN.\". |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=19 November 1932 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16935627 |title=AN AUSTRALIAN OPERA. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=6 December 1932 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=15 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The musical was revised and performed again in March 1933 at the Mosman Town Hall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16955408 |title=\"COLLITS' INN\". AT MOSMAN. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=25 February 1933 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n</ref> It was also broadcast on ABC radio in June of that year. However it was turned down for professional production by J.C. Williamsons Ltd.\n\n===F. W. Thring===\nVarney Monk sent the script to Frank Thring and went down to Melbourne to play him the score.  Thring was enthusiastic about the show and decided to produce it professionally. He hired an all star cast, putting Gladys Moncrieff, Australia's most popular star of light opera under a 12-month contract to play the lead. He also brought back two Australians from overseas to appear opposite her, Robert Chisholm and Claude Fleming, and hired the most popular comic of the day, George Wallace, to play the comic support role of Dandy Dan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17033105 |title=MUSIC AND DRAMA. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=16 December 1933 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nWallace's presence in the cast meant his part was expanded and he was given as many songs as Glady Moncrieff; in addition, parts were found for his regular collaborators, Marshall Crosby and [[John Dobbie]]. Extra lures to the theatre-going audience was a revolving stage, the first of its kind used in Australia, and the performance of an aboriginal corroboree at the beginning of Act Two.\n\nThe resulting production debuted in December 1933. It was a widely publicised occasion, attended by the state premier and lord mayor and the first act was broadcast live on Radio 3KZ. \"All this excitement over an Australian show with an all-Australian cast\", wrote Thring's biographer, Peter Fitzpatrick. \"Nothing like it had happened before. Frank [Thring]... must have felt like a king... It was certainly the most triumphant night of his life.\"<ref>Fitzpatrick p 199</ref>\n\nThe show was a big success, receiving excellent reviews and playing for sixteen weeks and over a hundred performances at the Princess.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11724052 |title=MUSIC, DRAMA & FILMS \"COLLITS' INN\". |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=26 December 1933 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n</ref> It went to Sydney for eight weeks, then had a three-week return season in Melbourne in October 1934.\n\nThe success of the musical encouraged Thring to expand his theatrical productions. Thring commissioned Monk to write a sequel, ''[[The Cedar Tree (musical)|The Cedar Tree]]'' and also revived ''[[The Beloved Vagabond (play)|The Beloved Vagabond]]''.<ref>Fitzpatrick p 203</ref>\n\n===Cast of 1933 Princess Theatre production===\n*Gladys Moncrieff as Mary Collits\n*Marshall Crosby as Pierce Collits\n*Robert Chisholm as John Lake\n*Claude Flemming as Robert Keane\n*George Wallace as Dandy Dick\n*Phyllis Baker as Sandy\n*John Dobbie as Toby\n\n==Proposed film version==\nThring intended to make a movie out of the play but died in 1936 before he had the chance to shoot little more than sound tests.<ref>Graham Shirley and Brian Adams, ''Australian Cinema: The First Eighty Years'', Currency, 1989 p122</ref><ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17039526?searchTerm=%22streets%20of%20london%22%20thring&searchLimits=sortby=dateAsc|||l-category=Article%7Ccategory%3AArticle 'ENGLISH PLAYS To be Filmed in Melbourne', ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', Friday 12 January 1934 p 6]</ref> A six-minute sound test of [[Gladys Moncrieff]] and Robert Chisolm singing 'While the Stars Are Shining', with a spoken introduction by [[Frank Harvey (Australian screenwriter)|Frank Harvey]] survives.<ref>[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=collit's%20inn;querytype=;rec=8;resCount=10 Clip at National Film and Sound Archive]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Harvey had reportedly written a screenplay.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61874368 |title=STACK ASIDES. |newspaper=[[Townsville Daily Bulletin]] |location=Qld. |date=29 October 1934 |accessdate=7 December 2012 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the words of theatre historian John Thompson:\n<blockquote>Collits\u2019 Inn was hailed as a unique Australian musical. It was not the first theatrical production to use Australian settings, nor was it, as is commonly claimed, the first Australian musical... [It] was not The Great Australian Musical many hoped it would be. But it proved that Australian creativity and talent could produce an original work that Australian audiences wanted to see and was judged worthy of a place on the world stage.<ref name=\"john\">[http://www.australianmusicals.com/article_itsaustralian.htm John Thompson, \"It's Australian and It's Good\", National Library of Australia News, Dec 2003, reproduced in ''Australian Musicals''] accessed 4 October 2013</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*Fitzpatrick, Peter, ''The Two Frank Thrings'', Monash University Press 2012\n\n==External links==\n* [http://muchamore.id.au/The_Play.html Article on ''Collits' Inn'', the play]\n* [http://www.australianmusicals.com/article_itsaustralian.htm ''It's Australian and It's Good''] article on history of the show by John Thompson at [[National Library of Australia]] News\n*[http://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/work/1889 Collits Inn] at [[AusStage]]\n\n[[Category:Australian musicals]]\n[[Category:1932 musicals]]\n", "name_user": "Loriendrew", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collits%27_Inn_(musical)"}
{"title_page": "In Concert (iamamiwhoami album)", "text_new": "{{under construction|placedby=danBLOO|nosection=yes}}\n<!--{{in use}}-->\n{{notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{primary|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = IN CONCERT\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[iamamiwhoami]]\n| cover      = iamamiwhoami; IN CONCERT.jpg\n| released   = {{Start date|2010|12|04|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = November 2010\n| venue      = [[Handen]], Sweden\n| genre      = \n| length     = {{duration|h=1|m=04|s=10}}\n| label      = To whom it may concern.\n| director   = Robin Kempe-Bergman\n| producer   = [[Claes Bj\u00f6rklund]]\n| chronology = [[iamamiwhoami]]\n| prev_title = [[bounty (album)|bounty]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[kin (iamamiwhoami album)|kin]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = IN CONCERT\n | type        = live\n | single1     = .\n | single1date = 4 December 2010\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Film cover\n | type    = live\n | cover   = iamamiwhoami; IN CONCERT (2016).jpg\n | border  = yes\n | alt     = \n | caption = 2016/2017 release\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''In Concert''''' (stylized in [[all caps]]) is the first live audiovisual performance installation by Swedish audiovisual project [[iamamiwhoami]], and also their first full-length release. The performance video was streamed on the project's independent label's website, To whom it may concern., on November 16, 2010, and released as a digital album on December 4, the same year, the project's one-year anniversary. For the project's seven-year anniversary in 2016,<ref name=\"trailer\"/> the film was made available for download and streaming,<ref name=\"vod\"/> and released on DVD on April 10, 2017.<ref name=\"twimc3\"/>\n\nThe one-hour performance takes place in [[Handen]], Sweden, with a single attendee chosen by followers to represent the audience.\n\n==Background and performance==\n{{infobox\n| above = Set list\n| bodyclass = floatleft\n| bodystyle = margin-right:1em\n| datastyle = text-align:left\n| data1 = \n{{ordered list|list_style=margin-left:2em\n| \"u-1\"\n| \"b\"\n| Interlude: \"Prelude 699130082.451322-5.4.21.3.1.20.9.15.14.1.12\"\n| \"t\"\n| Interlude: \"20101001\"\n| \"n\"\n| \"o\"\n| Interlude: \"13.1.14.4.18.1.7.15.18.1.1110\"\n| \"u-2\"\n| Interlude: \"15.6.6.9.3.9.14.1.18.21.13.56155\"\n| \"y\"\n| \"9.20.19.13.5.723378\"\n| \".\"\n}}\n}}\n\nTwo months since the release of \"y\", the seventh episode from the ''[[bounty (album)|bounty]]'' audiovisual series and album, a video requesting a volunteer was uploaded to iamamiwhomami's channel on October 1, 2010.<ref name=\"vogue\"/> This would be the first time the project addressed the audience directly, but not the first message the project delivered.<ref name=\"mtv-mail\"/> At the time, no official confirmation regarding who was behind the act, the internet's speculation already had name for the woman in the videos, Swedish singer-songwriter [[Jonna Lee (singer)|Jonna Lee]].<ref name=\"billboard\"/><ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref name=\"mtv-jonna\"/>\nFollowing the cryptic nature of the project, the video instructed viewers to choose their representative by October 8, with full name, phone number, and address, with no explanation of the purpose.<ref name=\"yt20101001\"/> This resulted in fans choosing YouTube user Hillary ''tehhils'',<ref name=\"forsakenorder-20101001\"/> who had to decline claiming difficulties to obtain a passport and suggested to pass on the task to German<ref name=\"aqnb\"/><ref name=\"lonelyleaf\"/> user ''ShootUpTheStation''. Subsequently, a video documenting a phone call made by Jonna Lee to the volunteer was uploaded on November 9, where she interviews him with questions about things like health, phobias, habits, and beliefs, ending with \"we will pick you up to the airport\" and requesting him to \"film [his] entire journey\".<ref name=\"yt20101109\"/> A series of six short videos from ShootUpTheStation's camera were uploaded from November 12 to 15, in which he documented his journey and his stay at a hotel where multiple visitors would come in to deliver a lesson.<ref name=\"volunteer-playlist\"/><ref name=\"jwz\"/>\n\nOn November 15, 2010, a concert was finally announced on a video titled \"http&#58;&#47;&#47;towhomitmayconcern.cc&#47;\",<ref name=\"yt-announcement\"/><ref name=\"vogue\"/> which would later become the label's website and store.\n\nThe performance consist of the 7 ''bounty'' songs released in 2010, as well as the third ''[[bounty (album)|bounty]]'' prelude \u2014which would later have a studio version released as \"LIKE HELL\" on ionnalee's ''[[Everyone Afraid to Be Forgotten|EVERYONE AFRAID TO BE FORGOTTEN]]''\u2014, and a new song known as \".\" ({{lang|sv|punkt}}) \u2014studio version later released as \"shadowshow\" on ''[[Blue (iamamiwhoami album)|BLUE]]''\u2014. The interludes are also some of the preludes, and music from the promos leading to the concert.\n\n==Release==\nThe concert video installation began streaming at approximately 00:15 CET on November 16, 2010, on the label's website, lasting 64 minutes and was available to be viewed for three additional hours on the site.<ref name=\"higherplain\"/> The project went inactive after this, until it was released as a single-track album on digital stores and streaming platforms on December 4, 2010,<ref name=\"itunes\"/> coinciding with the audiovisual group's one-year anniversary. Along with the album release, singles for some songs from the performance were made available: \"b\", \"t\", \"n\", \"o\", \"u-2\", \"y\", and \".\" (pronounced \"{{lang|sv|[[wikt:punkt#Swedish|punkt]]}}\";<ref name=\"gaynight-interview\"/> \"period\" in [[Swedish language|Swedish]]).<ref name=\"itunes-iam\"/>\nIn 2013, the album and its singles were pulled from all retailers.<ref name=\"iambf\"/>\n\nAgain, for the project's seventh anniversary on December 4, 2016, the film was released for download and on-demand streaming, and then a DVD edition came on April 10, 2017. These film digital and physical editions have a new artwork designed by Jacob Hulmston. The album has not been reissued on any format and remains unavailable.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline      = \n| total_length  = 1:04:10\n| all_lyrics    = Jonna Lee\n| all_music     = Jonna Lee and Claes Bj\u00f6rklund\n| title1        = ''IN CONCERT''\n| length1       = 64:10\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n<ref name=\"twimc3\"/>\n\n;Music\n* [[Jonna Lee (singer)|Jonna Lee]] \u2014 composition, lyrics, vocals, instruments, mixing\n* [[Claes Bj\u00f6rklund]] \u2014 composition, instruments, mastering\n\n;Film\n* Robin Kempe-Bergman \u2014 direction\n* John Strandh \u2014 cinematography\n* Bj\u00f6rn Baumann \u2014 sound\n* Agust\u00edn Moreaux \u2014 production design, styling, costumes\n* Klara Bj\u00e4rkstedt \u2014 costumes\n* To whom it may concern. \u2014 production\n* Jonna Lee \u2014 executive production\n\n;Artwork\n* Jacob Hulmston \u2014 graphic design (2016/2017 film release), cover art (2016/2017 film release)\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Label !! Release !! Format\n|-\n| 16 November 2010 ||rowspan=\"4\"| To whom it may concern. || Film || Streaming\n|-\n| 4 December 2010 || Album ||rowspan=\"2\"| {{hlist|Download|streaming}}\n|-\n| 4 December 2016 ||rowspan=\"2\"| Film\n|-\n| 10 April 2017 || DVD\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"mtv-mail\">{{cite news |last=Montgomery |first=James |date=2010-03-05 |title=iamamiwhoami Makes Contact, Sends MTV News a Package |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2578011/iamamiwhoami-mail/ |url-status= |work=[[MTV News]] |location=New York |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20100308031423/https://newsroom.mtv.com/2010/03/05/iamamiwhoami-mail/ |archive-date=2010-03-08 |access-date=2020-04-04 |via=Wayback Machine}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"mtv-jonna\">{{cite news |last=Montgomery |first=James |date=2010-03-15 |title='iamamiwhoami': Is Swedish Singer Jonna Lee Behi