{"title_page": "Travis Boak", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Travis Boak\n| image = Travis Boak 2018.1.jpg\n| caption = Boak playing for Port Adelaide in 2018\n| fullname = Travis Boak\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|08|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Geelong, Victoria|Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = [[Geelong Falcons]] ([[TAC Cup]])\n| draftpick = No. 5, [[2006 AFL draft#2006 national draft|2006 national draft]]\n| debutdate = Round 12, 2007\n| debutteam = {{AFL PA}}\n| debutopponent = {{AFL Ess}}\n| debutstadium = [[Football Park|AAMI Stadium]]\n| height = 184&nbsp;cm\n| weight = 85&nbsp;kg\n| position = [[Australian rules football positions#Midfield|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = {{AFL PA}}\n| guernsey = 10\n| years1 = 2007\u2013\n| club1 = {{AFL PA}}\n| games_goals1 = 265 (171)\n| sooyears1 = 2020\n| sooteam1 = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1 = 1 (0)\n| nationalyears1 = 2014\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Australia international rules football team|Australia]]\n| nationalgames_goals1 = 3 (0)\n| statsend = round 1, 2020\n| repstatsend = 2020\n| careerhighlights = \n* [[List of Port Adelaide Football Club captains|Port Adelaide captain]]: 2013\u20132018\n* 2\u00d7 [[All-Australian team]]: [[2013 All-Australian team|2013]], [[2014 All-Australian team|2014]]\n* 2\u00d7 [[John Cahill Medal]]: 2011, 2019\n* [[Showdown Medal]]: 2013 (round 3)\n* [[AFL Rising Star]] nominee: [[2007 AFL Rising Star|2007]]\n}}\n\n'''Travis Boak''' (born 1 August 1988) is a professional [[Australian rules football]]er playing for the [[Port Adelaide Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL). Boak [[List of Port Adelaide Football Club captains|captained]] the club from 2013 to 2018, and is a dual [[All-Australian team|All-Australian]] and dual [[John Cahill Medal]]list. He received a nomination for the [[2007 AFL Rising Star]] award in round 19 of the 2007 season.\n\n==AFL career==\n[[File:Travis Boak 2017.jpg|thumb|175px|left|Boak playing in 2017]]\nBoak was selected with {{AFL PA}}'s first selection and fifth overall in the [[2006 AFL draft]] from the [[Geelong Falcons]] in the [[TAC Cup]]. He made his AFL debut in a 31-point victory in round 12 of the 2007 season against {{AFL Ess}}. Boak continued to rise since his debut, accumulating 23 possessions against the {{AFL WB}} in only his third match. The following week, against {{AFL Ric}}, Boak kicked his first ever AFL goal. In round 19 against {{AFL Car}}, he earned a [[NAB Rising Star]] nomination for his 28 possessions and 2 goals. Boak's went on to play in the Port Adelaide team which competed in the [[2007 AFL Grand Final]] against {{AFL Gee}}, losing by a record margin. At the start of 2008, Boak picked up where he left off, playing a greater role in the Port Adelaide midfield alongside senior players such as [[Domenic Cassisi]], [[Kane Cornes]] and [[Shaun Burgoyne]]. He played in 17 games and averaged 20.1 disposals. Boak continued to improve in 2009 winning the Gavin Wanganeen Medal and averaging 23.7 disposals for the season.\n\nThe 2010 season was Boak's best season to date with a career best average of 23 possessions per game. His season ended with a flourish when he kicked three goals in each of the final two rounds. He became the first-tagged player in the Port Adelaide midfield and finished the season with 16 [[Brownlow Medal]] votes. The 2011 season saw Boak play in 21 games and lead the club in disposals (458), clearances (79) and inside 50s (85). He along with [[Jackson Trengove]] were jointly crowned the [[John Cahill Medal]]list, the first time that there had been a tie at the club's best and fairest award since 1893.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portadelaidefc.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/6038/newsid/123604/default.aspx|title=Historic Tie in Medal|publisher=Port Adelaide|date=16 September 2011|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2013 season, Boak was announced as the captain of the club, therefore replacing his number 10 guernsey with number 1, in accordance with Port Adelaide tradition.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.portadelaidefc.com.au/news/2013-01-30/boak-becomes-69th-captain|title=Boak to lead new era at Port Adelaide|date=30 January 2013|accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref> 2013 was considered to be Boak's best AFL season up to that point, with an average of 25.3 disposals a game, and kicking a season best of 20 goals. He was named in the [[2013 All-Australian team]]. In 2014, Boak continued where he left off from 2013, averaging a career best 26.6 disposals a game and tolling a season best 21 [[2014 Brownlow Medal|Brownlow]] votes to finish equal 4th. He was named in the [[2014 All-Australian team]], his second consecutive selection.\n\nBoak shifted between the midfield and half-forward over the following few seasons. In 2019, after stepping down from the captaincy at the end of the previous season, Boak made a permanent shift back to the midfield, enjoying career-best numbers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaskin|first=Lee|title=The masterstroke that has Power veteran in Brownlow mix|url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2019-04-26/the-masterstroke-that-has-power-veteran-boak-a-brownlow-fancy|work=afl.com.au|date=26 April 2019|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gaskin|first=Lee|title=Boak relishing not being Power's beast of burden|url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2019-05-01/boak-relishing-not-being-powers-beast-of-burden|work=afl.com.au|date=1 May 2019|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref> He played his 250th match in the Power's loss to {{AFL Col}} in round 7, becoming the fourth player to notch up 250 AFL matches for the club.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guthrie|first=Ben|title=Pies win big after scintillating start renders Port powerless|url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2019-05-03/match-report-collingwood-v-port-adelaide-r7-2019|work=afl.com.au|date=3 May 2019|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref> Boak would go on to win his second John Cahill Medal after averaging a career-best 30 disposals,<ref>{{cite news|last=Whiting|first=Michael|title=Port veteran clinches second B&F award - eight years after his first|url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/91720/port-veteran-clinches-second-bf-award-eight-years-after-his-first|work=afl.com.au|date=5 October 2019|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Colangelo|first=Anthony|title=Boak wins second Power best and fairest|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/boak-wins-second-power-best-and-fairest-20191004-p52xr3.html|work=[[The Age]]|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref> before having a shoulder operation in the off-season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaskin|first=Lee|title=No problem for rising Power mid Houston after knee issue|url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/366723/no-problem-for-rising-power-mid-houston-after-knee-issue|work=afl.com.au|date=20 January 2020|accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n:''Statistics are correct to the end of round 1, 2020''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Travis Boak|url=https://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/T/Travis_Boak.html|work=AFL Tables|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Australian rules football statistics legend}}\n{{AFL player statistics start with votes}}\n|- style=\"background:#EAEAEA\"\n| scope=\"row\" text-align:center | [[2007 AFL season|2007]]\n| {{AFL PA}}\n| 10 || 14 || 4 || 3 || 101 || 124 || 225 || 51 || 38 || 0.3 || 0.2 || 7.2 || 8.9 || 16.1 || 3.6 || 2.7 || 0\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" text-align:center | [[2008 AFL season|2008]]\n| {{AFL PA}}\n| 10 || 17 || 9 || 4 || 175 || 167 || 342 || 88 || 64 || 0.5 || 0.2 || 10.3 || 9.8 || 20.1 || 5.2 || 3.8 || 2\n|- style=\"background:#EAEAEA\"\n| scope=\"row\" text-align:center | [[2009 AFL season|2009]]\n| {{AFL PA}}\n| 10 || 18 || 7 || 5 || 223 || 204 || 427 || 81 || 73 || 0.4 || 0.3 || 12.4 || 11.3 || 23.7 || 4.5 || 4.1 